We rewrite \(\sin x + \sin 2x\) using the sum-to-product identity: \[ \sin x + \sin 2x = 2 \sin \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right) \cos \left(\frac{x}{2}\right) \] Thus, the equation becomes: \[ a \cdot 2 \sin \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right) \cos \left(\frac{x}{2}\right) = \sin 3x \] Using the identity \(\sin 3x = 2 \sin \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right) \cos \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right)\), we divide both sides by \(2 \sin \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right)\) (assuming \(\sin \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right) \neq 0\)): \[ a \cos \left(\frac{x}{2}\right) = \cos \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right) \] This simplifies to: \[ a = \frac{\cos \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right)}{\cos \left(\frac{x}{2}\right)} \] We analyze the function \(f(x) = \frac{\cos \left(\frac{3x}{2}\right)}{\cos \left(\frac{x}{2}\right)}\).
